<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-06-28T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-06-28T13:00:00-05:00" n="1286" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1286">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.115/314</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">El Paso</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-06-28T11:00:00-07:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 28, 1917—11 a.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>My June 27, 5 p.m.<note n="2" xml:id="d1286fn2">Not printed.</note>
                            Chihuahua Mining Company received telegram last night from Chihuahua
                            agent: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>We had to loan forcibly to the Government five thousand pesos
                                    which they will discount from taxes. We could not avoid it.</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <p>Hard to justify this as they have ample money in Juarez and plan to run
                            train with military escort to Chihuahua to-day.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Cobb</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>